  "prompt": "Are there legal obligations for financial institutions regarding money laundering?",
  "response": "Yes, financial institutions have significant legal obligations regarding anti-money laundering (AML) efforts. These typically include:\n\n1. Customer Due Diligence (CDD)\n- Verifying customer identities\n- Screening customers against watchlists\n- Understanding customer financial activities\n\n2. Reporting Requirements\n- Filing suspicious activity reports (SARs)\n- Reporting large cash transactions\n- Maintaining transaction records\n\n3. Risk Assessment\n- Identifying potential money laundering risks\n- Implementing risk-based compliance programs\n- Conducting ongoing monitoring\n\n4. Compliance Training\n- Training employees on AML regulations\n- Establishing internal compliance procedures\n- Maintaining updated knowledge of regulations\n\n5. Legal Compliance\n- Following Bank Secrecy Act (BSA) regulations\n- Complying with international AML standards\n- Implementing Know Your Customer (KYC) procedures\n\n6. Record Keeping\n- Maintaining transaction documentation\n- Preserving customer identification records\n- Ensuring records are accessible for potential investigations\n\nFinancial institutions can face significant penalties, including fines and potential criminal charges, for failing to meet these obligations.\n\nThese requirements aim to prevent criminal financial activities and promote transparency in financial systems.",
